	            'interview' => 'INSPECTOR:  Mr. Pembroke, thank you for coming in to the station.\r\n\r\nMr. PEMBROKE:  Well, I guess I didn’t have much choice\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  Can we get you some coffee? Water?\r\n\r\nMr. PEMBROKE:  No, no let’s make this quick; I have other matters to attend to today.\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  Of course. As you know, the painting found hanging in your dining room was found to be a forgery by Malloy Restoration Services. We believe your paining was swapped with the forgery sometime during the evening of your house party.  \r\n\r\nMr. PEMBROKE:  So, it would seem.\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  Can you think of anything unusual that happened that evening?\r\n\r\nMr. PEMBROKE: (rolls eyes) Define unusual.\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  Well, was anyone acting nervous or unusual? Did anything out of the ordinary happen?\r\n\r\nMr. PEMBROKE:  Acting unusual? How about my entire family – my wife, my niece and nephew. All disappointments. I’m sure my wife is having an affair. My niece and nephew are sweet enough but hardly ambitious. My niece is in art school and has big dreams. She’s smart. I offered her a role in my company, she turned it down. My nephew can’t settle on an occupation but doesn’t see the need to work hard. I’ve told him I’m cutting his allowance until he makes a plan for his future. So, there’s been some family tension. \r\n\r\nAs for anything out of the ordinary; one of the guests, Charles Ives fainted. He was fine after sometime. Fortunately for him, my good friend Jerome Cambridge was in attendance. He is a physician and took care of Charles. He ordered all of us to bring Charles to the lounge to rest. Charles rested in the lounge and was able to rejoin us later on in the evening. Other than that, I have nothing.\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  Please don’t take my next question in a bad way. Please understand, I must ask. How has business been lately?\r\n\r\nMr. PEMBROKE:  How can I not take offense?! Look, we’ve hit a bit of a rough patch. My partner Mason Jarvis and I are not seeing eye to eye on business. We’ve taken a couple losses this year and have had to make decisions about how to manage the business moving forward. We have taken loans we owe money on. But why would I steal my own painting to collect the insurance? I can just sell the painting. Don’t believe what my wife says! I’m not in competition with my friends at the yacht and country clubs like she says!\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  I didn’t know that is her belief. I suppose you just answered my next question, but can you think of anyone that would want to frame you for the theft?\r\n\r\nMr. PEMBROKE: (laugh) My wife would love to see me fail. My niece and nephew aren’t happy I am cutting their allowances until they shape up. Maybe my business partner Mason would like to frame me too so he could just take over my share of the company, maybe even sell it and retire. What do I know? Look, are we done? I have a business meeting to attend.\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  Okay, Mr. Pembroke, you are free to leave. We will be in touch. Oh! One more thing. We don’t have a warrant yet, but you won’t mind us looking into your house, would you?\r\n\r\nMr. PEMBROKE:  I have nothing to hide. You have my permission to search my house.\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  Thank you. I appreciate your cooperation.',
