	            'interview' => 'INSPECTOR:  Hi Mrs. Pembroke, thank you for coming in. I have just a few questions.\r\n\r\nMrs. PEMBROKE:  Ask away.\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  On the night of the theft during the house party, did you notice anything unusual from anyone at the party?\r\n\r\nMrs. PEMBROKE:  I don’t know. I try to stay buzzed during my husband’s parties. It keeps things more interesting.  \r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  I take it you and Mr. Pembroke are having issues?\r\n\r\nMrs. PEMBROKE:  My husband works nonstop and is full of himself, constantly trying to impress people. It’s a bit much.\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  Fair enough. But back to my question, did you observe anyone behaving in an unusual manner?\r\n\r\nMrs. PEMBROKE:  My husband was irritated most of the night, but shows a smiling face during pictures. That’s fairly normal, I suppose. My niece wouldn’t stop yapping about the painting, and the painter. \r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  You seem to have come to the mansion way earlier than others. Any specific reason?\r\n\r\nMrs. PEMBROKE:  That’s true. I come early to let the house helpers enter the mansion and do the preparations for the party.\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  We understand Charles Ives is the esteemed art professor at your niece’s art school. Was he invited to the party by her?\r\n\r\nMrs. PEMBROKE:  Yes. My niece is a very ambitious girl. She hoped to impress Professor Ives by inviting him to our extravagant party and believed he would thoroughly enjoy the painting by Forester Snow as much as she. Professor Ives is a contemporary art professor and accomplished painter himself. I know she was looking to enter his professional circle. \r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  Fair enough. Now you work as a criminal defense attorney?\r\n\r\nMrs. PEMBROKE:  Correct. (smirking face) I suppose you are suggesting I would know how to commit a crime without getting caught?\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  (shaking head no) I would suggest no such thing. But Mrs. Pembroke, you do concede you and your husband are having marital issues. Are you also having financial issues?\r\n\r\nMrs. PEMBROKE:  I know you are just doing your job, but I find your questions insulting. I do plan to start my own law firm, so hopefully things will get better.\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  Fair enough. Okay Mrs., Pembroke, thank you for your time. We will be in touch. Oh! One more thing. We don’t have a warrant yet, but you won’t mind us looking into your house, would you?\r\n\r\nMrs. PEMBROKE:  Sure. You can do that if you wish to.\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR: Thank you!',
