        	[
	            'suspect_id'   => 3,
	            'interview' => 'INSPECTOR:  Professor Ives, thank you for meeting us here. We know you’re a busy man. We have some questions regarding the night the painting was stolen from the Pembroke Mansion. \r\n\r\nProf. IVES:  I understand.\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  We understand it was quite the evening for you! Tell us what happened in regards to your fainting spell.\r\n\r\nProf. IVES:  I’m not sure there’s much to tell. We’d finished coffee and dessert. I stood up like the rest. I’d been talking to Mr. Pembroke over dessert and we were planning to continue our conversation when all a sudden I felt faint and collapsed.\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  What had you two been discussing?\r\n\r\nProf. IVES:  I can’t recall. I think he was telling me about the history of the mansion. \r\n\r\nINSPECTOR: Okay so what happened next? You fainted, then what?\r\n\r\nProf. IVES:  I recall being moved to the lounge. Dr. Cambridge inquired about my health. My fainting spell was rather strange. I’d never experienced it before. But I have no allergies or medical problems I’m aware of. Maybe overexertion? I have a very busy lecture schedule this semester, consult for several museums, and have had to travel quite a bit. The doctor chalked it up to fatigue and ordered me to rest, which I did.\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR: Yes, Dr. Cambridge mentioned you received a text after you were brought into the lounge. Was it work related? Did you respond?\r\n\r\nProf. IVES:  Yes, work related, as usual (rolls eyes). No, I didn’t answer it and rested as Dr. Cambridge advised.\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  When did you rejoin the guests?\r\n\r\nProf. IVES: (thinks) I don’t know the exact time. It could have been 15-20 mins later. \r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  Do you recall what happened when you rejoined the guests?\r\n\r\nProf. IVES:  Well, the party was going as usual until Amanda ran towards me frantic telling me the painting…the same painting we’d been looking at all night was a forgery. I of course conceded the painting on the wall was suspicious and should be tested by a lab to verify.\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  How well do you know Amanda Pembroke?\r\n\r\nProf. IVES:  Not that well, actually. She is a graduate student at the university in which I teach. I’ve heard a lot about her on campus from my faculty colleagues, and other students. She is seen as obsessed with the painter, Forester Snow. I’ve heard, but of course cannot verify, that she has spent her graduate stipend trying to locate Snow, who has been reclusive since his major piece sold more than 2 decades ago.\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR: (shakes head in disbelief) Fascinating. You don’t know her well, have you any idea why she invited you to the party that evening?\r\n\r\nProf. IVES:  My best guess? She is trying to build her network and gain entry into my circle of artworld connections. I was surprised when she approached me, but admit, I was thrilled to be invited to see the original painting. Modern art is my specialty; it’s not uncommon for me to get invited to events by individuals I don’t know well, or at all. I have had modest success in my own right as a painter, and have authored numerous publications in the field of modern art…not to brag (grins)\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  Hey, if it’s true, it isn’t bragging! (grins) Professor Ives, since you barely know Amanda, is it also true you had never previously met any of the other guests, including her family before?\r\n\r\nProf. IVES:  I met Daniel and Marcia once previously.  I was trying to get the Black Square during its auction and they outbid me. \r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  Do you think it’s possible Amanda had something to do with the theft?\r\n\r\nProf. IVES:  I hate to think of anyone doing such a thing. I don’t know her that well, but I suppose it’s possible. Maybe she was trying to impress me. \r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  I notice that you are wearing gloves. Do you always wear them?\r\n\r\nProf. IVES:  I have dry skin lately (damn weather!). So, I have been wearing them, especially when I go outside my house.\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR: Okay, well thank you for your time, professor. One more thing. May we permission to search your home for the missing paining? It’s merely a formality and would save us the hassle of getting a warrant. \r\n\r\nProf. IVES:  (Laughs) You can search my house. I would like to stay with you when you do that though as I don’t want your people to be spoiling my paintings! \r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  Not a problem professor. You may be present during the search. Thank you, Professor.',
