	            'interview' => 'INSPECTOR:  Miss Pembroke, thank you for coming in today. As you were one of the guests at your uncles’ house party the night of the theft, we have a few questions.\r\n\r\nAMANDA:  I understand\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  Excellent. You are in art school, correct?\r\n\r\nAMANDA:  That’s right. I hope to obtain a high-profile position in an esteemed museum someday or start my own business. \r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  It sounds like you have big dreams. How well do you know Professor Charles Ives?\r\n\r\nAMANDA:  He is a professor of modern art in the same university I attend, and has had some success selling his work and has many connections that could be helpful to me in my future. My aunt Marcia agreed to me inviting him, but I think more because he’s is a local celebrity and she could get good press coverage when Ms. Abernathy would report our event in the local newspaper, rather than to help me.  \r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  Witnesses say you are the one that called out the painting in the dining room being a forgery.\r\n\r\nAMANDA:  That’s true.\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  Impressive from a young art student.\r\n\r\nAMANDA:  I don’t know what you’re implying.\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  Witnesses have described you as obsessed with the painting. You were observed looking at it at close range for long periods of time and engaging the professor in conversations about the painter.\r\n\r\nAMANDA: (Becomes flustered) Yes, that’s true, but I’m not obsessed! I’m writing my dissertation on the painter, Forester Snow. I’m focusing my specialty in modern art too. It is my dream to work in a museum and help curate works. I must become an expert to do that! And yes, I happened to notice the signature of the artist, Forester Snow looked different. I shared my suspicions with the professor!\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  How did he react?\r\n\r\nAMANDA: He seemed a bit annoyed. Like I’m some obnoxious student trying to show how smart I am. He agreed it was a forgery, but seemed reluctant. Probably he was mad I noticed it and he didn’t.\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  And at what time did you discover this?\r\n\r\nAMANDA:  I don’t remember the exact time but sometime around 11pm, and that’s when we called the police.\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  Miss. Blackburn, was anyone acting out of the ordinary? \r\n\r\nAMANDA: Well, just the usual tension between my aunt and uncle. And between my brother and uncle. But my brother wasn’t involved, I’m sure of it. Our uncle is really hard on Brandon and me. \r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  Isn’t it true your parents were arrested and convicted of embezzling money when you and Brandon were 14 and 16, respectively.\r\n\r\nAMANDA: (rolls eyes). Yes. So what? My uncle Daniel was thrilled to take over my parents remaining assets and our island retreat, which he made into his party mansion. He was less thrilled about being our guardians.\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  It sounds like you have a grudge against your uncle. He got to take over your house and your parents remaining assets and seems to relish in keeping you and your brother on a short financial leash. And by your own admission, he’s hard on you and your brother. If I were you, I’d want to get back at him.\r\n\r\nAMANDA:  I didn’t steal his precious painting! I don’t need to do that! I’m going to make it big without him. I don’t know how the painting was seemingly hanging in the dining room wall one minute and replaced by an obvious forgery. But that’s your job, why don’t you stop picking on me and figure it out.\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  Alright Miss Pembroke. Thank you for your time today. Just a heads up. Your aunt and uncle have given us permission to search all the family residences for the stolen painting.\r\n\r\nAMANDA:  I’ll try not to be insulted. I have nothing to hide so search away! \r\n\r\nINSPECTOR: Thank you!',
