	            'interview' => 'INSPECTOR:  Brandon, we appreciate your time today. We have just a few questions about the night the painting went missing at your uncle’s mansion.\r\n\r\nBRANDON: (Shrug) Okay, but I think you mean my parents’ mansion.\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  Sounds like you have a grudge against your uncle?\r\n\r\nBRANDON: (Sarcastic) Oh, I don’t know. He gets to take over my parents remaining assets, withholds money rightfully belonging to my sister and me, brags about his big business, which is obviously failing, and throws big parties at my mansion. He complains I never do anything but never once has he helped me. My parents made a mistake, they didn’t intentionally embezzle, they had a crappy accountant. Uncle Daniel knows this but saw an opportunity to take advantage of my family. \r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  Brandon, what do you do for living? \r\n\r\nBRANDON: (Silent for few seconds) Well, I didn’t need to do anything if my Uncle had not taken over my parent’s property. \r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  Okay. So how do you survive now since your uncle has your parent’s property? \r\n\r\nBRANDON: I get a monthly payment from the trust setup by my parents. My Uncle administers that.\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  I see. Though I hear your uncle will be stopping those payments. And if your uncle and aunt get caught in some criminal activity, who owns the property? \r\n\r\nBRANDON:  I am not a lawyer so don’t know all the details, but I think it would come to my sister and me as we don’t have any other close relative. \r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  Thanks Brandon. Did you happen to notice your sister acting strange during the party?\r\n\r\nBRANDON: (shocked) Amanda? No. I mean she wouldn’t shut up about the painter guy but basically all she talks about is art these days. I think a lot of people were annoyed but I didn’t care. I was mostly focused on my girlfriend, Sarah Abernathy.\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  The party photographer?\r\n\r\nBRANDON: Yeah.  (smirks) My uncle insisted on having the party documented and was willing to pay to have a story about the party at Walnut Grove Mansion published in the newspaper. I told him I know a photographer and journalist at the local newspaper and could arrange for her to cover the story. To my surprise he didn’t argue with me. (Smirks again). I just thought the world should see how dysfunctional my family is.\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  (laughs) You’re quite a comedian, Brandon. Is there anyone that stands out to you that could possibly be involved in the theft of your uncle’s painting?\r\n\r\nBRANDON:  Well, I wouldn’t rule out my uncle to do something like this. Possibly his business partner Mason Jarvis. I overheard them arguing a few weeks over money lost in the business. My uncle was furious Mason took a loan without telling him, claiming the terms were terrible. I’d also say my cold Aunt Marcia. She’s been unhappy with my uncle for a while. Maybe she stole it and is planning to use the money to leave my uncle. \r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  Okay Brandon, I think that’s all our questions for now. Just a heads up, your Uncle and Aunt have given us permission to search all your residences. \r\n\r\nBRANDON:  Whatever, bro. I’ve got nothing to hide.\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  Thank you!',
