        	[
	            'suspect_id'   => 8,
	            'interview' => 'INSPECTOR:  Mr. Jarvis, thank you for coming in today. As you were a guest at Mr. Pembroke’s dinner party the other night, we do have a few questions related to the painting theft. \r\n\r\nMASON JARVIS:  That’s fine.\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  How long have you been in business with Mr. Pembroke?\r\n\r\nMASON JARVIS:  We started our company almost 10 years ago. \r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  We understand there has been tension between the two of you recently; can you shed some light on this?\r\n\r\nMASON JARVIS: (annoyed) Shed some light on this? I’ll give it to you straight: the times are changing and Daniel is a dinosaur! He refuses to upgrade to even the most basic technology platforms to keep our business competitive. I have a background in using technology for marketing and advertising and I can do the upgrades myself! Daniel won’t budge…he’s too worried. With the marketplace changing we’ve fallen behind our competitors and as such, then business has taken a major hit. Daniel is too proud; I want to save the company so took out a loan. When I got around to telling Daniel a few weeks ago, he was furious and claims I can’t negotiate business and we’ll have to pay interest we cannot afford. So yes, there’s been tension recently. \r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  Enough tension to say, steal a painting to sell and recoup personal losses? \r\n\r\nMASON JARVIS: I find that question insulting! I didn’t steal the painting! If you think I did, go prove it!\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR: (calming voice) take it easy, Mr. Jarvis. It’s just a question. What kind of busines do you and Daniel run?\r\n\r\nMASON JARVIS: (calming down) We buy and sell art, primarily to hotels. That’s where most of our revenue comes from. I’ve told Daniel we should use our profits to branch out and restore artwork. Daniel thinks my venture would drain company funds. That’s what our big fight was about recently because I took out a loan to help branch out in this area without his approval. But I’ve got friends I trust in the industry and I say it’s a risk worth taking that could give our company more publicity.\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  So, if someone has to create a fake painting of a popular artist, you have contacts capable of doing that? \r\n\r\nMASON JARVIS:  It is possible, but I wouldn’t do it. It would be illegal.\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  Okay. Do you recall Professor Charles Ives fainting that evening?\r\n\r\nMASON JARVIS:  Yes\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  Do you recall approximately when he fainted, and what happened next?\r\n\r\nMASON JARVIS:  We’d just finished coffee and dessert. Professor Ives stood, and a moment later collapsed around 9pm. Dr. Cambridge looked at him and ordered us to help move the professor into the lounge. Daniel left to get him some water.\r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  Do you recall how long Daniel was out of the room?\r\n\r\nMASON JARVIS:  No. Maybe 5 minutes? I’m not entirely sure. \r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  Do recall anyone else leaving the room? Anyone missing from the room?\r\n\r\nMASON JARVIS:  I remember standing next to Brandon and Miss Abernathy, the photographer. So, they didn’t leave. Oh yes, Marica left for restroom; I don’t recall if anyone was missing from the room. Marcia later joined us when we went back to the dining room.  \r\n\r\nINSPECTOR:  Alright Mr. Jarvis, we won’t take any more of your time. One more thing. Although we don’t have a warrant yet, but you won’t mind us looking into your house. Would you? \r\n\r\nMASON JARVIS: No problem to me. Do it whenever you want to.',
